## Memory Hygiene Rules

| Rule | Why |
|---|---|
| Never delete lessons — only mark superseded | Deletion loses the history of why a rule existed |
| Never edit decisions without adding a superseding entry | Edits hide the reasoning trail |
| Todo items marked complete stay in the file for 1 session, then archived | Keeps todo.md actionable without losing history |
| Lessons are written in plain language — no jargon | They must be understood at session start in seconds, not decoded |
| Every lesson must have a prevention rule — observation alone is not a lesson | "X happened" is a log entry. "When X happens, do Y instead" is a lesson |
| Lessons are written by Zeus when corrections or gate failures happen — not auto-generated | Real lessons have prevention rules; stubs without content are noise |
| Session-end markers in `tasks/todo.md` should be cleaned when no active tasks exist | An empty todo file with 50 timestamps is not useful |

---

## Long-term Maintenance (keeping files useful)

These files grow over time. Without cleanup, they become noise that wastes context window instead of helping. Here is how to keep each file useful:

### `tasks/todo.md` — keep it short

- **Only active work** lives here. When a task is done, remove it after the next session.
- Session-end markers (`<!-- session-end ... -->`) are hook artifacts — clean them out periodically. They have no value once the session is over.
- If the file has no active tasks, it should just say `_No active checklist items._`

### `tasks/lessons.md` — quality over quantity

- **Real lessons stay.** A lesson with a clear prevention rule is valuable forever.
- **Stubs without a prevention rule** are noise, not lessons — delete them on sight.
- **When the file exceeds ~30 entries:** Zeus should consolidate similar lessons into grouped patterns (e.g., three "validation missing" lessons become one with a broader prevention rule). Mark the originals as superseded.
- **Quarterly review:** Skim the file and ask: "Is this lesson still relevant? Has the prevention rule actually helped?" Remove or update stale entries.

### `tasks/decisions.md` — archive when stale

- **Active decisions stay** in the main file — these are the ones that affect current work.
- **Superseded decisions** should be clearly marked with `Status: Superseded by [newer decision]`. They stay in the file for reference but can be moved to `tasks/decisions-archive.md` after 90 days if the file gets long.
- **When the file exceeds ~20 active entries:** Create `tasks/decisions-archive.md` and move all superseded entries there. Link from the main file: `_Older decisions: see [decisions-archive.md](decisions-archive.md)_`
- **Never silently edit a decision.** If a decision changes, add a new entry and mark the old one superseded.

### General rules

- **Context window budget:** Zeus reads all three files at session start. If the combined size exceeds ~200 lines of useful content, it is time to archive or consolidate. More than that and the files start competing with the actual task for context space.
- **Archival is not deletion.** Move old content to archive files (`tasks/decisions-archive.md`, `tasks/lessons-archive.md`) — do not throw it away.
- **The user decides** when to run a cleanup. Zeus can suggest it ("lessons.md has 35 entries, want me to consolidate?") but should not do it silently.

---

## What Memory Is Not

- Memory is not a chat log — it is structured, actionable knowledge
- Memory is not a status report — it is a prevention and decision system
- Memory is not optional — a session that doesn't write to memory has not fully completed its task
